Adjust rack to top position (top and middle positions for 4 servings) and preheat oven to 425 degrees.

Drain and rinse @chickpeas{1} in a #bowl{}; pat very dry with #paper towels{}. Halve, peel, and cut half the @red onion{1}(halved and cut into 1/2-inch-thick wedges) (whole onion for 4) into 1/2-inch-thick wedges.

Toss chickpeas and onion on a #baking sheet{} with a drizzle of @cooking oil{1%tsp}, half the @Italian seasoning{1/2%tbsp} (all for 4), @salt{to taste}, and @pepper{to taste}.

Roast on top rack until chickpeas are golden and tender and onion is caramelized, ~{18-20%minutes}. (You'll add more to the sheet after ~{11%minutes}.)

Meanwhile, wash and dry produce.

Halve @grape tomatoes{4%oz}. Dice @fresh mozzarella{4%oz} into 1/2-inch cubes.

Place tomatoes in a small bowl; toss with @balsamic vinegar{5%tsp}, @sugar{1%tsp} (2 tsp for 4 servings), and a big pinch of @salt{}.

Pat chicken or beef dry with #paper towels{} and season all over with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}. Heat a drizzle of oil in a large pan over medium-high heat. Cook chicken until browned and cooked through, 3-5 minutes per side, or cook @beef tenderloin filets{10%oz} to desired doneness, 4-7 minutes per side. Transfer to a #cutting board{}.

Halve @ciabatta bread{1} lengthwise; cut into 3/4-inch strips. Tear strips into rough cubes. Transfer to a large bowl; toss with @olive oil{2%tbsp}, @garlic powder{1%tsp}, @salt{to taste}, and @pepper{to taste}.

Once chickpeas and onion have roasted 11 minutes, remove from oven and push to one side of sheet; carefully add croutons to empty side. (For 4, add croutons to a second baking sheet; toast on middle rack.) Return to top rack until golden and crispy, ~{7-9%minutes}. Wipe out bowl.

Carefully transfer everything to bowl used to season croutons to cool.

Remove tomatoes from bowl and set aside, leaving marinade behind.

Whisk @mayonnaise{1%tbsp} and @Dijon mustard{1%tsp} into marinade until smooth. (For 4 servings, use all the mayonnaise and mustard.)

Slowly whisk in @olive oil{4%tbsp}, drizzling a little bit at a time, until creamy. Season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}. Reserve 1 1/2 tbsp dressing (3 Tbsp for 4) for serving.

Add @spinach{5%oz} to bowl with cooled chickpeas, onion, and croutons. Toss with remaining dressing until evenly coated.

Divide salad between plates. Top with mozzarella and tomatoes. Drizzle with reserved dressing and season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}. Serve.

Thinly slice chicken or beef against the grain. Serve atop salad.

> We love a good Caprese salad, so here's a bigger, better version that's chock-a-block with ingredients and totally dinner-worthy. Fresh spinach provides the leafy base with caramelized onion throughout for pops of sweetness. Crisp roasted chickpeas add a protein boost while garlicky ciabatta croutons up the crunch factor even more. Of course, it wouldn't be Caprese without the tomatoes and fresh mozzarella, but we made them bite-size so they're more fork friendly. A creamy balsamic dressing ties it all together with Caprese's characteristic flair.